<div class="answer-block">
  <h2> 3. </h2>
  <p>
    Suppose a normal student with basic privileges in AIT has an interesting idea for an event. He can then login to our
    service and then create the event with a proper name as well as a description for it. The user with admin privileges
    can then decide whether to approve the event or reject it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Other normal users can log in and view all the events. If they are interested in any particular event they can learn
    more about the event as well as set up personalized email notifications for the events they are interested in.
  </p>

  <p>
    The user with administrative privileges can monitor various events. For example - The SU president will be the
    administrator and will have complete access over the events. He can also create events for all the official events
    happening in the university.
  </p>

  <p>
    As the head of SU committee, the user can create events for his committee. Under the event, he can also send
    invitations, calls for volunteers and provide updates for the event.
  </p>

  <p>
    Other users who are the faculty can also view different events happening in the university and they can also set up
    notifications for the events. For example - Any Phd thesis happening in the university.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="answer-block">
  <h2>4. Offline alternatives </h2>
  <p>Offline alternatives to the event management app would be a personal diary to keep track of one’s events and
    sending out invitations via post for the events.
  <p>
</div>

<div class="answer-block">
  <h2> 5. Online alternatives </h2>
  <dl>
    <dt>Google calendar</dt>
    <dd>Google calendar has excellent feature of creating events and sending out invites. It also allows users to keep
      track of all the events in a particular time period (day, month, year). Similarly, a Google calendar can be
      created for a particular organization so that all the events of the organization can be viewed in one place.
    </dd>
    <dt>Event Pop! , Eventbrite</dt>
    <dd>These are event management web applications especially designed for companies and charity organizations. The
      main highlights of these apps are the multi-language support, feature of selling tickets for the event, sending
      out invitations and tracking the number of attendants for the events. The events can also be categorized so users
      can easily browse through their events of interests. These apps even shows recommendations based on the user’s
      previous activities.However, admin approval is required for creating the events and full company details has to be
      provided to sign up.
    </dd>
    <dt>Facebook events</dt>
    <dd>Facebook also provides the functionality of creating an event page and send out invitations for the event using
      facebook or even through email. It can also keep track of the people who have accepted the invitations. It also
      allows updates in the event by posting the photos of the events. It basically creates a facebook profile for the
      event.
    </dd>
  </dl>
</div>

